description:
I graduated Washington State University with an MS in Mathematics, and have been working as a data engineer for the past few years. Even though I went to school to be a data scientist, my passion has evolved to data engineering - building scalable pipelines that ingest, run ETL, and spit out production ready data. I think most data scientists are thrown a similar curveball when first breaking into the industry and it's because most places that want to do data science don't yet have data! Although intimidated at first, I have come to love and embrace the engineering role, realizing the importance of developing solid software engineering principles in order to build bulletproof applications. On the horizon for me is to learn more about Docker and Kubernetes, Spark (through EMR and PySpark), Airflow, streaming services (Kafka, Kinesis), and Golang.

I love my job, I love the people I work with, and I'm forever grateful to those who have guided me along the way. As I'm always learning new things, I would love to connect to discuss theories, business, or anything else!

Please check out my GitHub to see some of my side projects.

Thank you for your time!
headline: Data Engineer at CirrusMD Inc.
mutualConnectionsText: 1 mutual connection: James Van, M. A., CDF (he/him)
jobDescription2:
- Set up an AWS Data Lake and multiple ETL pipelines to process disparate data asynchronously using multiple tools (s3, Step Functions, SQS, Glue, Athena, Lambda, Redshift, Redshift Spectrum).
- Architect a standardized solution across multiple teams to serve as the central data repository.
- Use Terraform to set up a repeatable infrastructure on AWS for any new teams that may pop up. Includes creating S3 buckets and configuring their properties to send event notifications to SQS, altering the SQS access policy to allow communication, and setting up Glue tables.
- Host open source spaCy NLP models (14 languages) on AWS EFS to be called via API Gateway and Lambda functions. This allows for CI/CD of production models.
- Lead a project to host prodigy (https://prodi.gy) on EC2 to allow data labeling for better model inference.
- Create other Python applications that ingest data via batch REST API calls and application databases that ultimately push raw data to AWS on a schedule (cron and Windows Task Scheduler). Hosted on EC2 and other relevant networks.
- Productionize a scalable consumer-facing Levenshtein-based fuzzy string matcher microservice via Lambda. Ran large scaled parallelized tests with Sagemaker to determine ~98% precision and ~60% recall - but this worked for our use case as we wanted to optimize precision.
- Set up email alerts using SNS, Lambda, and SES to inform a key email list about system failures.
- Use API Gateway and Lambda to expose our data in a controlled manner.
- Work with SQL to construct stored procedures and views to enhance data for analysts.
- Build dashboards in Tableau that portray data in meaningful and insightful ways for the client.
- Work towards quantifying what has been considered qualitative to come up with objective measurements that can capture the effectiveness of our work.
- Collaborate with assessments and engagement specialists to gather and analyze data that we feel helps fulfill our objectives.

Among the top 20 students in UC San Diego selected for HDSI's Undergraduate Research Scholarship Program. The team was awarded $5000 to conduct state-of-the-art Recommender Sytems Research.

Project: Optimizing Recommender Systems At Scale
Mentor: Prof Julian McAuley

• This project lies at the intersection of state-of-the-art ML systems research and recommender systems
• Historically, this is an area that hasn't received much academic or industry attention which is reflected by the fact that only 2% of papers published are related to Recommender Systems.
• This is still a very important field given the ubiquity of recommender systems in most major online platforms and how computationally intensive they tend to be.
• In this project, I study and develop better ways to deploy recommender systems at scale efficiently by taking into account things like query arrival patterns and query sizes to utilize computational resources much more effectively.

description:
My name is Emily, and I'm a Data Scientist and Engineer. My educational background and early work experience started in healthcare, where I sought to make an impact through scientific discovery. My eventual decision to become a Data Scientist was rooted in my desire to increase my international presence and contributions with more industry-transferable skills. All of my work experience share a theme of communication, where it was essential to produce clear analytics reports that were digestible for various audiences, from scientists and physicians to stakeholders and C Suites.

Recently, I've been getting more interested in the extraction, transformation, and loading of event data from open media sources (GDELT, Reddit, Twitter, other) for developing Early Warning and Detection systems for areas of conflict. I'm fascinated by the various machine learning methodologies of extracting this information, and I'm keen on working on projects and for companies that enable me to grow and enhance my skillset in this particular subset of data modeling.

I have tailored most of my data projects and career choices towards international, philanthropic, initiatives, and I find that my work performance exceeds expectations when I am able to particulate in global initiatives that seek to improve the lives of others (in some fashion) around the world. 

Competencies:
Python, SQL, Command Line, RedShift, BigQuery, MySQL, PostGIS, Airflow, PySpark, Databricks, Data Factory, Seaborn, Random Forest Classifier, Linear Regression, K-Nearest Neighbors, Machine Learning, TensorFlow (keras), Convolutional Neural Networks, U-Nets
headline: Data Engineer at UNICEF
jobDescription2:
Department: Risk Analysis and Preparedness Section (RAPS), Office of Emergency Operations (EMOPS)

Premise of Task: Contextual Alert and Trend System (CATS) is a proof of concept (POC) for an automated system for near real-time media monitoring via GDELT to identify trends and anomalies in the volume of online reports about pre-defined indicator events, at country level. The tool fills a critical gap in structured risk information gathering for UNICEF’s Horizon Scan process and will support CO level risk management activities. This POC follows an analysis of existing tools that finds no appropriate products.

Outcomes
1. Validate ability to accurately identify anomaly and trends using statistical analysis
2. Provide structured information gathering and alerting for UNICEF’s global Horizon Scan process
3. Contribute to UNICEF’s ability to improve CO risk informed programming

Key Words: PySpark, R, Azure Data Factory, PostgreSQL, Azure Databricks, Azure Data Lakes Storage, Microsoft SQL Server (TSQL), Power BI, GDELT, ACLED

description:
I am happy when I am writing code. I am happier still when the code works. And happiest when the code transforms into an innovative solution. Trust me when I say this: I am transported to a different place when I write code and I can do it tirelessly (so long as I have some Doritos to munch on by my side). Of course nothing comes easy. There is frustration now and then, but the key lies in not giving up (and perhaps a bit of Googling). My experience has taught me no problem is beyond a solution, even if the solution is hidden behind multiple failed attempts. 
Data gives me my share of dopamine. It makes me tick. Give me data and I will start figuring out patterns, marking outliers-- in short joining the dots to reveal the whole picture. Data speaks to me like none other. I am here to decipher the cryptic language of data for those who don’t understand it. Get in touch if you want me to tell you the story the data is trying to tell.  I have more than eight years of experience in developing database and ETL programs. I have led a team of developers working on both backend development and front-end management.

jobDescription:
•	Developed Apache presto and Apache drill setups in AWS EMR (Elastic Map Reduce) cluster, to combine multiple databases like MySQL and Hive. This enables to compare results like joins and inserts on various data sources controlling through single platform. 
•	The AWS Lambda functions were written in Scala with cross-functional dependencies that generated custom libraries for delivering the Lambda function in the cloud. 
•	Performed raw data ingestion into S3 from kinesis firehouse, which triggered a lambda function and put refined data into another S3 bucket and wrote to SQS queue as aurora topics. 
•	Writing to the Glue metadata catalog allows us to query the improved data from Athena, resulting in a serverless querying environment. 
•	Created Pyspark frame to bring data from DB2 to Amazon S3. 
•	Created AWS RDS (Relational database services) to work as Hive metastore and could combine 20 EMR cluster's meta data into a single RDS, which avoids the data loss even by terminating the EMR. 
•	Built a Full-Service Catalog System which has a full workflow using Elasticsearch, Kinesis, CloudWatch. 
•	Leveraged cloud-provider services when migrating on-prem MySQL clusters to AWS RDS MySQL, provisioned multiple AWS AD forests with AD-integrated DNS, as well as utilized AWS Elasticache for Redis. 
•	Used AWS Code Commit Repository to store their programming logics and script and have them again to their new clusters.

•	I have created ETL pipelines to write the data into snowflake using Spark snowflake connector. And, once the data is in the snowflake, I have created intermediate tables to generate input feature data for machine learning models based on the use case, then also once the data is in the snowflake tables have also created ETL pipelines to export the data into feature store. 
•	The data from feature store and retrain the models, and deploy them using the AWS sage maker, Python SDK is for both online and offline prediction analysis.
•	I've also used Cloud watch to create monitoring policies on top of some of the AWS tools. I was also building feature store pipelines using by SDKs for Amazon Sage maker. 
•	I have created, AWS lambda functions to kick off the downstream process. When we have a new file change or modification in the s3 bucket. I'm reading, this using PI Spark these files and transforming.
•	I have contributed on creating Kafka snowflake connector and write the data from the topics into a staging area and finally writing it into the snowflake tables, that was one I have created ETL pipelines to write the data into snowflake using Spark snowflake connector. 
•	I have created a separate monitoring policy for each table, if it's successful, then only the adoption process dependent on that table would be triggered. This is all done in EMR air flow.
•	I have implemented source table monitoring policies because it's very important to have the single source of data. And also I have to check that the feature data and anything that we are creating for models is in the right format, otherwise there would be drift in the models, the statistical distribution would be varied and it would impact the model output.
•	Migrating the Pyspark jobs to AWS glue so that AWS glue can take care of spinning up the resources. AWS lambda functions to kick off the ETL pipelines based on the event trigger-based mechanism when there are any new files that are coming into s3.

description:
Hey! How are you doing? 
Thank you for landing on my LinkedIn profile page. Before you scroll down to weigh me against my technical and leadership qualities, let me narrate my summary to you in 'About' section here.

I would love to describe myself in 5 simple points.

1. Assets: What I bring to the table? Detail-driven, creative and critical thinking, solid problem solving abilities, effective and clear communication styles, commitment of a team player, quality-rich questions, punctuality and thus the enthusiasm to reach the deadlines gracefully.

2. Education and Profession: Where did the above come from? The above qualities I mentioned are gained while I got educated and earned my Bachelor's Degree in Computer Engineering and polished them well and groomed my professional communication skills as a Data Engineer when I worked for CitiusTech. I worked with my team where our goals were aligned. The drive to accomplish the tasks and deliver the best bagged me as the youngest person to receive CitiusTech Core Value award for 'Passion in All your Work'.

3. Post-graduation in US: What piqued my curiosity to resume my education after 3 yrs.? I flew to the west and landed in Texas, US to pursue MS in Business Analytics and Data Science. Data Engineering which I learned during my career path is sandwiched between Business Analytics and Data Science. If you see, these three basically form a cycle. The inputs from each one feed the other. Working with both the teams kicked my curiosity juices to gain expertise in these fields.

4. Soul foods: Read and listen (audio-books and podcasts) because it enlightens me. Cooking is my stress buster. Yoga brings the calmness to my anxiety and it helps me balance my curious nature (clarity about what things to get curious for). Singing connects me with people and teaches me to be harmonious with my surrounding. Hiking helps me pump out my creative thinking in the midst of nature. Learning new language is always fun for me and a tool to connect with people. Music is my food.

5. Prospect and Goals: To cut this short, my goal is first to be a rational human being for what I think and decide. I see my future self to be more bold and aware with respect to treatment with lots and lots of data and their veracity, to enhance myself technically, emotionally and cognitively to be a formidable data scientist and surpass my limits to become an awe-inspiring author, to never stop loving and make this world more lovely than yesterday.
 
P.S. This is what my resume doesn't reflect so I put it all up here.

description:
I went to the University of Washington in 2015 to study one of my passions: Oceanography. While participating in research on the oceanographic aspect of state of the art climate models (CMIP5), I discovered a love for computer programming. This led me to obtain a second major, Informatics, which combined with my previous work helped me receive an internship offer at Nike where I interned during the summer of 2018. After going back to school the following year, I was fortunate to have the opportunity to create and teach two new classes at the University of Washington, School of Oceanography focused on oceanographic data science. Following speaking at graduation, I left the Seattle area to rejoin Nike in a full time capacity. Ever since I have been solving critical business problems in machine learning (Tensorflow, scikit-learn), data science (Python, Anaconda, Jupyter Notebooks) and data engineering (Python, SQL, Airflow, AWS, Snowflake), and look forward to continuing in this line of work for the rest of my career. I especially enjoy solving large, complex problems, often utilizing multiple technologies / skillsets mentioned above and frequently combine this with my expertise in working with geospatial data.

I have found there is nothing more important than continuous learning and improvement. To assist with this I am currently pursuing a master's degree at UC Berkeley in Information and Data Science while continuing to work full time.

She pursued her MS in Masters in Management of Science and Engineering at Columbia University in the City of New York. During her course capstone project with Louis Vuitton, she built a recommendation system for stores, omni channels, and digital sales in North America.
